│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The transformation performed by IndVarSimplify rewrites an icmp samesign ugt  │
│ between a loop-invariant i32 and a zero-extended loop-varying i8 value (%x    │
│ ugt zext %call2) into an icmp samesign ugt between the truncated              │
│ loop-invariant i8 (%x trunc to i8) and the original loop-varying i8 (%call2). │
│ The original compare cannot produce poison because both operands are known    │
│ non-negative: %x has a range metadata [0,32), and zext %call2 yields [0,256). │
│ After the transformation, %call2 can be negative (e.g. 0x80 = -128 as         │
│ signed), while %x remains non-negative. The samesign flag now imposes a       │
│ constraint that is no longer guaranteed, making the comparison potentially    │
│ produce poison, thus introducing new undefined behavior not present in the    │
│ source. Alive2 correctly reports the target as less defined.                  │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ LoopSimplify first creates the preheader (SplitBlockPredecessorsImpl). Then   │
│ IndVarSimplify performs the rotate-out-of-loop transformation for (icmp       │
│ unsigned zext(V), Invariant). The transformation site is in                   │
│ IndVarSimplify.cpp lines 1522–1535: the lambda doRotateTransform replaces the │
│ operands with the un-extended variant and a trunc of the invariant. No code   │
│ adjusts or drops the samesign flag. This is the first semantic-altering       │
│ transformation with respect to poison production.                             │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ The logic in IndVarSimplify assumes replacing zext(Op) with Op and trunc(RHS) │
│ preserves correctness for unsigned predicates. That holds for ordinary        │
│ unsigned comparisons, but with the samesign flag, zero extension provided an  │
│ implicit proof that the loop-varying operand was non-negative. Removing zext  │
│ invalidates that proof. The pass fails to recompute or conservatively drop    │
│ the samesign flag. As a result, the transformed icmp may produce poison when  │
│ the varying operand is negative, whereas the original never did.              │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/IndVarSimplify.cpp, lines 1526–1535 (inside  │
│ the doRotateTransform lambda). Insert code after setting the new operands to  │
│ conservatively clear the samesign flag if present, because the transformation │
│ may have weakened sign information. A precise analysis (e.g. using            │
│ ValueTracking to re-establish sign equality) could be added later, but        │
│ conservative clearing is correct and sufficient to fix the miscompile.        │
│                                                                               │
│ Patch logic to add:                                                           │
│ if (ICmp->hasSameSign()) { ICmp->setSameSign(false); }                        │
│ Include explanatory comment referencing loss of guaranteed non-negativity     │
│ from removed zext.                                                            │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ Dropping the samesign flag after rotating the zext out restores semantic      │
│ equivalence by preventing introduction of new poison conditions. The original │
│ comparison was always defined; the transformed one must also be always        │
│ defined. This change ensures IndVarSimplify does not incorrectly preserve     │
│ samesign in cases where its preconditions no longer hold.                     │
